      <hedline>
        <hl1>Build Highways Fit for Cities</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Carolyn Konheim letter on July 14 article on reassessing highways cites success of regional planning in Paris region; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As Americans reassess their highways (front page, July 14), they should look at the Paris region, comparable to our metropolitan area.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As Americans reassess their highways (front page, July 14), they should look at the Paris region, comparable to our metropolitan area.</p>
        <p>There, 82 percent of the land is parks, farms or forest, compared with 30 percent here. French towns retain an urban character in clusters around rail lines, which reach central Paris in under an hour. They allow development only if it fits a regional plan.</p>
        <p>Here, hundreds of local governments operate with no plan and are prey for developers who say they will add to tax coffers or go elsewhere. The result is helter-skelter building that clogs roads and worsens global warming. Even with a regional tax base, people would join the sprawl because of mortgage deductions, cheap energy and gas taxes dedicated to highways. One solution is a gradually increasing fee on the carbon content of fuels that would be earmarked to reduce the national debt.</p>
        <p>CAROLYN KONHEIM  Nantucket, July 14, 1999</p>
      </block>
